She turned to a blank page and wrote down the date. Below it, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" asked Ivory, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away now."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The King of Ice never let Kari go out because, in his eyes, she was "a mistake." She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, which otherwise consisted solely of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she spoke out about her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had changed as well. She was given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
He or she also had to remain in the princess's service, but that wasn't too bad, because it gave him or her a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, isn't it?" asked Ivory, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad gleam in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As he asked the question, he remembered what she had said last time.
No, hit Kari out of the way. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but iel remembered the servants' and townspeople's outrage. Iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Um... what do you feel like doing?" they asked. Kari looked up enthusiastically. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when they looked at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" said Ivory, turning toward the silent princess, who was frantically typing and shaking her bedhead back and forth. "Yes?" Iel chuckled slightly, seeing the usually reserved princess become so enthusiastic about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and that wasn't in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" proposed Ivory as she got up and made her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and once again lost herself in her memories, wrapping herself back up in her thick comforter.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that were not her responsibility, like paint.
He/She turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the servants' whispers.
"I heard she was possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered their ears, because trying to ignore them wasn't working. Iel headed toward the royal painter's chamber, which was in the east wing, the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately crafted as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who, according to legend, had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around the room, easels covering every last centimeter of the walls. Surprisingly, iel saw none of that. The room was clean, and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool right in front of it. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, having his portrait painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! You're coming to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" Aquilo asked Ivory, giving him a wink.
"Pardon, little prince," he replied, partly ignoring her, as he searched for the items his silent friend desired. "I'm here just to pick up supplies."
"Ah, the girl is going to leave very soon?" asked Aquilo. "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on their list and placed them in a box they had discovered. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought of that, however. "Oh my dear, you know well it's just a phase! It'll pass when you grow up!" he muttered.
"I have to go," he said, suddenly uncomfortable, because of the prince's words, which reminded him of all the bad things people said about his gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Are you leaving us already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the royal painter's complaints.
